        // So, $M_2 \le a_{2n-(k_2+1)}$.
        //
        // We know $k_1+k_2 = n-1$.
        // So $M_1 \ge a_{k_1}$.
        // And $M_2 \le a_{2n-(n-1-k_1+1)} = a_{2n-n+1+k_1-1} = a_{n+k_1}$.
        //
        // Thus, $M_1 \le M_2$ implies $a_{k_1} \le M_1 \le M_2 \le a_{n+k_1}$.
        // The difference $|M_1 - M_2|$ is minimized when $M_1$ is as large as possible and $M_2$ is as small as possible.
        //
        // Consider the partition where $C_1$ consists of $a_0, \dots, a_{k_1-1}, a_{n-1}, a_{n+k_1}, \dots, a_{n+2k_1-1}$
        // This is getting complicated.
        //
        // The simplest way to think about it is that the $n$-th smallest element ($a_{n-1}$) and the $(n+1)$-th smallest element ($a_n$)
        // are the "middle" elements of the entire sorted array.
        //
        // If we can make $a_{n-1}$ the median of one class and $a_n$ the median of the other, then the difference is $a_n - a_{n-1}$.
