        // This is because if $M_1 \ge a_n$, then $C_1$ would contain $k_1+1$ elements $\ge a_n$.
        // And $C_2$ would contain $k_2+1$ elements $\ge M_2$.
        // This would mean at least $(k_1+1) + (k_2+1) = n+1$ elements are $\ge a_n$.
        // But there are only $n$ elements $\ge a_n$ in the sorted array ($a_n, \dots, a_{2n-1}$).
        // This is a contradiction. So $M_1$ must be $\le a_{n-1}$.
        //
        // Similarly, if $M_2 \le a_{n-1}$, then $C_2$ would contain $k_2+1$ elements $\le a_{n-1}$.
        // And $C_1$ would contain $k_1+1$ elements $\le M_1$.
        // This would mean at least $(k_1+1) + (k_2+1) = n+1$ elements are $\le a_{n-1}$.
        // But there are only $n$ elements $\le a_{n-1}$ in the sorted array ($a_0, \dots, a_{n-1}$).
        // This is a contradiction. So $M_2$ must be $\ge a_n$.
        //
        // So we must have $M_1 \le a_{n-1}$ and $M_2 \ge a_n$.
        // This implies $M_2 - M_1 \ge a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        //
